# Kasten Lab – Version 0.1

## Disclaimer

This is version 0.1 of the Kasten Lab. It contains 6 questions based on a Veeam Kasten environment.

It is important to note that this lab is not directly related to Veeam Software. It was created and is independently maintained by a community member and should be used strictly for study, testing, and validation purposes.

It is strongly discouraged to use it for anything related to production environments.

---

### 1
You are responsible for operating a Kubernetes-based environment protected by Veeam Kasten. During a routine validation exercise, you are asked to ensure that a new workload running in the `world-dev` namespace is properly protected.

As part of this, you should create a backup policy named `world-dev-backup` that initially follows an on-demand execution model and is strictly scoped to resources identified by the `world-dev` namespace.

Once created, you are expected to verify that at least one backup execution completes successfully, as this will be considered evidence that the policy is correctly functioning.

---

### 2
After confirming the backup execution, you are instructed to investigate the underlying storage behavior of the platform.

Access the Longhorn web interface and locate the persistent volume associated with the application that was just protected by the backup policy.

Within that volume, identify the snapshot that has been generated as a result of the backup operation and confirm its existence and correctness, as this snapshot will be relevant for recovery validation.

---

### 3
As the environment evolves, a new storage target must be introduced for off-cluster protection.

You are required to create a new Location Profile using an S3-compatible backend and name it `minio-kasten-lab`.

This profile should be fully functional and reachable from Kasten, and it must be validated as healthy before it can be used as a backup export destination.

---

### 4
Following this, the previously created backup policy `world-dev-backup` must be modified to reflect a more production-like schedule.

The execution mode should be changed from on-demand to a daily schedule running at 11:00 PM.

At the same time, retention rules must be introduced so that snapshots are retained for exactly one day.

The policy must also be extended to export backups to the newly created Location Profile `minio-kasten-lab`, ensuring that exported backups follow the same retention expectations as snapshots.

Once these changes are applied, you are expected to trigger a manual execution of the policy to validate the configuration, and if necessary, run the manual execution so that it expires within a short window of two hours.

---

### 5
In a separate scenario, you are asked to demonstrate your ability to reproduce a backup policy from scratch under updated operational requirements.

A new policy named `homer-demo-backup` must be created. It should be configured to run every day at 10:00 PM.

It should target the `world-dev` namespace, maintain a snapshot retention of one day, and export all backups to the previously defined `minio-kasten-lab` Location Profile.

The expectation is that this policy not only exists but is actively functioning, meaning at least one successful execution must be observed, with manual execution allowed if required under a two-hour expiration constraint.

---

### 6
You are informed of a change request affecting an application called `homer-demo`.

The development team requires a modification in the way this application is exposed, but instead of directly editing the live system, you are expected to restore the most recent available backup into a completely new namespace called `homer-demo-new`.

After restoration, you must adjust the application’s ingress configuration so that the access hostname changes from `homer-xxx` to `homer-xxx-new`, while preserving the same base domain.

For reference, the original ingress configuration provided by the developer is:

```yaml
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: Ingress
metadata:
  name: homer-demo-ingress
  namespace: homer-demo
spec:
  ingressClassName: traefik
  rules:
  - host: homer-xxx.conza.xyz
    http:
      paths:
      - path: /
        pathType: Prefix
        backend:
          service:
            name: homer-web
            port:
              number: 80
